The paper deals with game theory and learning algorithms in security games, which are typically studied in the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of algorithms to learn the optimal defender commitment, which falls under the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The paper also addresses the issue of attacker manipulation, which is a security concern and is studied in the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The paper proposes a game-theoretic framework and algorithms to compute the optimal defender policy, which involves optimization and decision-making, and thus falls under the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses simulations to evaluate the proposed approaches, which falls under the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
